[2026-05-18T13:13:22+01:00] CRITICAL_PATH_REVIEW — doc-count-drift — M1 evidence:
  Plan rationale (§2 M1, line 27): "M1 touches no docs but the scope-filter
  logic is the L-007 fix — its absence is itself a doc-drift hazard"
  (without scope filtering, `ruff format` would mutate ALL .py files
  repo-wide, including those whose docstrings carry hardcoded counts —
  precisely the Tier 6 detector domain).
  Evidence M1 closes this hazard:
  (a) stage_b_scope() computes scope set via `git diff --name-only
      main...HEAD` — claude-code/commands/sole-dev-merge.md (see "Stage B"
      bash block); covers Python + shell.
  (b) ruff format and `ruff check --fix` are invoked ONLY on $CHANGED_PY
      (in-scope) via `echo "$changed_py" | xargs -r ruff …`. Empty input
      ⇒ xargs -r no-ops; non-empty ⇒ one path per ruff arg, all in-scope.
  (c) L-007 guard at end of stage_b_scope iterates `git diff --name-only
      HEAD` and `git checkout HEAD --` any file NOT in $changed_files.
      Empirically verified by bats test "Stage B: L-007 guard reverts
      out-of-scope drift, in-scope ruff fix lands" (test_stage_b_scope.bats
      @test 1 → ok 1).
  (d) Empirical full run (this milestone, isolated tmp git repo): planted
      out-of-scope dirty file `tests/codemem/foo.py` ⇒ post-stage-B
      `git diff tests/codemem/foo.py | wc -c` = 0 bytes.
  Verdict: PASS — scope-filter + L-007 guard structurally prevent the
  doc-count-drift hazard. The Tier 6 detector remains the secondary safety
  net for any hardcoded-count drift introduced by other means (e.g., docs
  written by hand).
